Furthermore, the work at maximal efficiency $W_{\mathrm{M}\eta}$ is of no interest in standard thermodynamic cycles, since it corresponds to the work performed by the cycle working at its Carnot limit, which is known to vanish. In the case of OTE cycles, however, $W_{\mathrm{M}\eta}$ is positive for any non-zero value of $\alpha$, and is very close, for ideal cycles, to $W_{\mathrm{max}}^{\mathrm{OTE}}$. Finite work at asymptotically unitary efficiency is thus the most peculiar characteristics of our OTE cycles, impossible to achieve in standard equilibrium contexts.
